\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this lab,
 we familiarized ourselves with using communication protocols (SPI and I2C,
 respectively) to communicate to peripheral devices with our CC3200 Microntroller Unit (MCU).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We used the SPI protocol to interact with an Adafruit SSD1351 OLED Digital Display (OLED),
 and perform drawing operations on it's screen.
 Using the general-purpose pins provided by the MCU,
 we can bind the signals defined by the SPI protocol and initiate communication via the SPI software development kit API.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Then,
 we introduce I2C to extract acceleration data in 3 dimensions,
 from three registers defined by the MCU's on-board BMA222 Accelerometer.
 We focus on the x and y dimensions,
 determining the tilt & angle of the MCU in 8-bit 2's complement form,
 from two respective registers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Combining our ability to communicate with the OLED and determine accelerometer information,
 we can tilt the accelerometer and get a velocity response from drawn pixels on the OLED.
 Mainly,
 we move a circle around the OLED display.
 More information on how this works will be included in subsequent sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In completing this lab,
 we effectively learn how to work with MCU-supported communication protocols,
 and get it to do exciting things with peripheral devices,
 as well as utilize on-board MCU components to introduce additional functionality to these peripheral device programs that we otherwise wouldn't have.
\end_layout

