\begin_layout Subsection
Implement OLED Interface Using SPI
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Arguably the most involved checkoff in this lab,
 this involves setting up the SPI communication protocol to write commands and their subsequent data to the OLED display,
 and implementing the API provided by Adafruit to draw various shapes on the display (as well as producing the coding framework needed to use some of these API calls effectively).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
One need to carefully set up the SPI pins,
 and then use the tools which the SDK provides to create functions that allow for the OLED API to be implemented;
 namely completing 
\family typewriter
writeCommand()
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
writeData()
\family default
.
 This happens in 
\family typewriter
Adafruit_OLED.c
\family default
.
 More on this in Methods!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Turning our attention to 
\family typewriter
main.c
\family default
,
 the systems programmer needs to ensure the SPI is configured properly;
 this ended up being quite touchy,
 and required careful consideration of the values that we could edit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Lastly,
 a main 
\family typewriter
while(1)
\family default
 loop needs to be set up to invoke the appropriate drawing functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The main lessons from this checkoff consists of working around the software inconviences of Texas Instruments SDK's and open-source firmware.
 Getting this program working requires a careful touch,
 which will be detailed in methods.
 This lab works as a good primer for the kind of attention to detail required of embedded systems design.
 It also helps to explore the low-level requirements of working with peripheral devices like the OLED,
 and the kind of necessities needed for supporting the functionality the programmer desires,
 both in terms of software and hardware.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Verifying SPI waveforms using a Saleae logic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This lab introduces the Saleae Logic Analyzer,
 and it's corresponding software Saleae Logic 2.
 This is an important debugging tool in the arsenal of an embedded systems programmer,
 allowing for easy verification of signal traces for up to 4 pin-outs (organized by 4 channels in the Saleae Logic 2).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Checkoff 2 also helps understand the analog component underpinning the software we have written,
 and contextualizes not only what our software is doing,
 but how the SPI protocol is working.
 We get a feel for what a serial clock should look like,
 what the MOSI (data line) should look like for the OLED,
 as well as how the DC,
 Reset,
 and CS pins shThould behave.
 The analyzer provides an incredibly powerful snapshot of all of this working in concert,
 and how different systems can communicte with each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Controlling the BMA222 accelerometer with I2C
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In this checkoff,
 we get familiar with using the on-board BMA222 accelerometer to determine the orientation of the MCU,
 and eventually,
 use it's output to produce interesting results with peripheral devices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The checkoff consists of running the 
\family typewriter
i2c_demo
\family default
,
 and verifying the output from the registers defined by the BMA222 (indicating the tilt of the MCU).
 The SDA and SDL pins are used to interact with the I2C protocol,
 and we use the UART protocol to type commands in the terminal to read the values of specific registers (indicating the accelerometer axis values at the time of printout).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sliding Ball
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In Checkoff 4,
 we bring it all together,
 combining the BMA222 with the OLED,
 enabling a ball to move on the screen.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This checkoff requires that you extract the relevant values from the BMA222 registers (x and y),
 and use them in a formula to simulate a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

natural acceleration
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 increase for the central coordinate points of a small circle on the OLED display.
 It requires careful consideration of how these values are used as scalar multiples;
 their 2's complement nature also needs to be carefully handled (signed versus unsigned integers).
 Ultimately,
 this checkoff teaches careful data type application and conditional control of math operations in the context of embedded systems,
 allowing for fine-tuned coordination of pixels on the OLED!
 Pretty neat.
\end_layout

